node.text:
Drop a 💙 FOR THIS MOMENT OF KINDNESS
•
One small act of kindness could make the largest difference in someone else’s life. It doesn’t even have to be something as large as this. You could help someone pick up fallen papers, help a coworker with something they were struggling with. It will not only make a difference to them, but also to you. You feel different when you allow positivity and kindness to be a part of your day to day.

It’s so easy to look at the world and see the “Bad.” The Media doesn’t focus on Good stories because those seldom get high ratings. The TRUTH is though...good deeds outweigh bad by 100 to 1.

Why is someone filming the traffic and accidentally recording this scene? 🤔Whatever - granny has safely arrived on the other side of the street - that's probably what counts.

node.text:
The American usage is very similar to the British, with the exception that “the” is always used:

He is in the hospital. = He is a patient. It's necessary to have been actually admitted as a patient to be “in the hospital.”

He is at the hospital. = He is working there, making a delivery, visiting a patient, etc. This would also be used if someone is is just having an appointment with a doctor or undergoing a medical test. (“He is at the hospital, having a CT scan.”)

British English would delete “the” from the first meaning, but retain it in the second.
